384–1420":"1384–1420","1390–Male":"1390–Deceased","1327–1372":"1327–1372","1329–Female":"1329–Deceased","1327":"1327","1355":"1355","1420":"1420","1375":"1375","about 1389":"about 1389","1384":"1384","1395":"1395","1372":"1372","1382":"1382","1390":"1390","1329":"1329","1417":"1417","Faversham, Kent, England":"Faversham, Kent, England","Battle, Sussex, England":"Battle, Sussex, England","England":"England","Sussex, England":"Sussex, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Baker","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: occupational name, from Middle English <i>bakere</i>, Old English <i>bæcere</i>, a derivative of <i>bacan</i> ‘to bake’. It may have been used for someone whose special task in the kitchen of a great house or castle was the baking of bread, but since most humbler households did their own baking in the Middle Ages, it may also have referred to the owner of a communal oven used by the whole village. The right to be in charge of this and exact money or loaves in return for its use was in many parts of the country a hereditary feudal privilege. Compare   Miller  . Less often the surname may have been acquired by someone noted for baking particularly fine bread or by a baker of pottery or bricks.","Americanized form (translation into English) of surnames meaning ‘baker’, for example Dutch   Bakker  , German   Becker   and   Beck  , French   Boulanger   and <b>Bélanger</b> (see   Belanger  ), Czech <b>Pekař</b>, Slovak <b>Pekár</b>, and Croatian   Pekar  .","History: Baker was established as an early immigrant surname in Puritan New England. Among others, two men called Remember Baker (father and son) lived at Woodbury, CT, in the early 17th century, and an Alexander Baker arrived in Boston, MA, in 1635."],"variants":[{"name":"Miller","meanings":["English and Scottish: occupational name for a miller. The standard modern vocabulary word represents the northern Middle English term <i>miller</i>, an agent derivative of <i>mille</i> ‘mill’, reinforced by Old Norse <i>mylnari</i> (see   Milner  ). In southern, western, and central England   Millward   (literally, ‘mill keeper’) was the usual term. In North America, the surname <i>Miller</i> has absorbed many cognate surnames from other languages, for example German <b>Müller</b> (see   Mueller  ), Dutch   Mulder   and   Molenaar  , French   Meunier  , Italian   Molinaro  , Spanish   Molinero  , Hungarian <b>Molnár</b> (see   Molnar  ), Slovenian, Croatian, and Serbian   Mlinar  , Polish <b>Młynarz</b> or <b>Młynarczyk</b> (see   Mlynarczyk  ). <i>Miller</i> (including in the senses below) is the seventh most frequent surname in the US.","South German, Swiss German, and Jewish (Ashkenazic): variant of <b>Müller</b> ‘miller’ (see   Mueller  ) and, in North America, also an altered form of this. This form of the surname is also found in other European countries, notably in Poland, Denmark, France (mainly Alsace and Lorraine), and Czechia; compare 3 below.","Americanized form of Polish, Czech, Croatian, Serbian, and Slovenian   Miler   ‘miller’, a surname of German origin."]},{"name":"Baxter","meanings":["English: occupational name from Middle English <i>baxter</i> ‘baker’ (from Old English <i>bæcestre</i> ‘baker’, earlier ‘female baker’, the feminine equivalent of <i>bæcere</i>). Compare   Baker  ."]}]},{"name":"John","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["New Testament: ‘God is gracious’.  See  <b>John</b> ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":27,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"When John Baker VII was born in 1355, in Sussex, England, his father, John Baker VI, was 28 and his mother, Mrs. John Baker, was 27. He married Joane Fryer about 1389, in England. They were the parents of at least 2 sons. He died in 1395, in his hometown, at the age of 40."},"et":{"1355–1395":"1355–1395","1375–1417":"1375–1417","1384–1420":"1384–1420","1390–Male":"1390–Surnud","1327–1372":"1327–1372","1329–Female":"1329–Surnud","1327":"1327","1355":"1355","1420":"1420","1375":"1375","about 1389":"umbes 1389","1384":"1384","1395":"1395","1372":"1372","1382":"1382","1390":"1390","1329":"1329","1417":"1417","Faversham, Kent, England":"Faversham, Kent, England","Battle, Sussex, England":"Battle, Sussex, England","England":"England","Sussex, England":"Sussex, England"},"fi":{"1355–1395":"1355–1395","1375–1417":"1375–1417","1384–1420":"1384–1420","1390–Male":"1390–Kuollut","1327–1372":"1327–1372","1329–Female":"1329–Kuollut","1327":"1327","1355":"1355","1420":"1420","1375":"1375","about 1389":"noin 1389","1384":"1384","1395":"1395","1372":"1372","1382":"1382","1390":"1390","1329":"1329","1417":"1417","Faversham, Kent, England":"Faversham, Kent, England","Battle, Sussex, England":"Battle, Sussex, England","England":"England","Sussex, England":"Sussex, England"},"fr":{"1355–1395":"1355–1395","1375–1417":"1375–1417","1384–1420":"1384–1420","1390–Male":"1390–Décédé","1327–1372":"1327–1372","1329–Female":"1329–Décédée","1327":"1327","1355":"1355","1420":"1420","1375":"1375","about 1389":"environ 1389","1384":"1384","1395":"1395","1372":"1372","1382":"1382","1390":"1390","1329":"1329","1417":"1417","Faversham, Kent, England":"Faversham, Kent, Angleterre","Battle, Sussex, England":"Battle, Sussex, Angleterre","England":"Angleterre","Sussex, England":"Sussex, Angleterre","lifeSummary":"Lorsque John Baker VII est né en 1355, à Sussex, Angleterre, son père, John Baker VI, avait 28 ans et sa mère, Mr